INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When using the Relationships model in Tableau's logical layer, which statement BEST describes how Tableau handles aggregation compared to a traditional physical-layer Join?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Relationships pre-aggregate all tables at data source save time, improving dashboard load speed"},{"id":"b","text":"Relationships perform aggregation automatically at query time, preserving row context for each table and avoiding duplicate rows"},{"id":"c","text":"Relationships require the analyst to manually define aggregate calculations to prevent row multiplication"},{"id":"d","text":"Relationships always produce a Full Outer Join at the database level, then aggregate in Tableau's engine"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Per the source material, the Relationships model (logical layer) 'preserves context, automatic aggregation.' Unlike physical joins that can inflate row counts (fan-out), Relationships aggregate each table at the appropriate granularity automatically at query time, preventing duplicate rows without requiring manual intervention. They do not pre-aggregate at save time, do not require manual aggregation calculations, and do not simply produce a Full Outer Join.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/relate_tables.htm","label":"Tableau – Relate Your Data (Relationships)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
