INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst is using data blending in Tableau and notices that the secondary data source only contributes aggregated values to the view. What is the correct explanation for this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The secondary source is a Live connection, which forces aggregation before rendering"},{"id":"b","text":"Data blending always aggregates the secondary source's data before joining it to the primary source at the view level"},{"id":"c","text":"Tableau automatically converts the secondary source to an Extract to improve performance"},{"id":"d","text":"The analyst must define a join calculation to enable row-level detail from the secondary source"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Primary data source has full data; secondary contributes aggregates.' Data blending is a view-level operation where the secondary source is aggregated by the linking field before being associated with the primary source. This is a fundamental characteristic of blending — it does not provide row-level detail from the secondary source. The other options incorrectly attribute the aggregation to connection type, Extract conversion, or join calculations.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/multipleconnections.htm","label":"Tableau – How Data Blending Works"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst is using data blending in Tableau and notices that the secondary data source only contributes aggregated values to the view. What is the correct explanation for this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Tableau feature would an analyst use to visually build a data preparation flow with steps such as Input, Clean, Aggregate, and Output — BEFORE loading data into Tableau Desktop for analysis?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Tableau Desktop Data Source page"},{"id":"b","text":"Tableau Prep Builder"},{"id":"c","text":"Tableau Server Content Manager"},{"id":"d","text":"Tableau Public Web Editor"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Per the source material, 'Tableau Prep Builder is a visual data prep tool' with steps including Input, Clean, Pivot, Join, Union, Aggregate, Script, and Output. It is specifically designed for preparing and shaping data before analysis. The Tableau Desktop Data Source page offers some data preparation features (like Pivot and Split) but is not a dedicated visual flow-based prep tool with Aggregate and Script steps. Tableau Server Content Manager manages published content. Tableau Public Web Editor is for simple chart editing.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/prep/en-us/prep_get_started.htm","label":"Tableau – Getting Started with Tableau Prep Builder"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
