INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data analyst connects to a large SQL Server database in Tableau Desktop. After publishing the workbook to Tableau Server, end users report slow dashboard load times. Which connection type change would most directly improve dashboard performance for end users without requiring them to wait for live queries?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Switch from a Live connection to an Extract connection and schedule the extract to refresh nightly."},{"id":"b","text":"Switch from an Extract connection to a Live connection to bypass caching."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable Tableau Bridge on the analyst's local machine."},{"id":"d","text":"Change the database driver to an ODBC connector."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A Tableau Extract (.hyper) pre-aggregates and compresses data locally, so queries run against the extract rather than the live database, significantly improving dashboard load times for end users. A Live connection queries the database on every interaction, which is slower. Tableau Bridge is used for on-premises data sources with Tableau Cloud, not primarily for performance. Switching drivers does not inherently reduce query latency.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/extracting_data.htm","label":"Tableau – Extract vs. Live Connections"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data analyst connects to a large SQL Server database in Tableau Desktop. After publishing the workbook to Tableau Server, end users report slow dashboard load times. Which connection type change would most directly improve dashboard performance for end users without requiring them to wait for live queries?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst needs to combine a Salesforce data source with an Excel spreadsheet in a single Tableau workbook so that fields from both sources can be used on the same worksheet. Which feature should the analyst use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Data Blending"},{"id":"b","text":"Cross-Database Join"},{"id":"c","text":"Union"},{"id":"d","text":"Relationship"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Relationships are the recommended method since Tableau 2020.2 for combining tables from different data sources at the logical layer. Cross-Database Joins are also possible but require the sources to be in the same logical connection. Data Blending is a legacy workaround with limitations such as non-additive aggregations. A Union stacks rows of tables with identical schemas and does not combine different source types. Relationships allow Tableau to intelligently join tables at query time based on context.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/relate_tables.htm","label":"Tableau – Relate Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst needs to combine a Salesforce data source with an Excel spreadsheet in a single Tableau workbook so that fields from both sources can be used on the same worksheet. Which feature should the analyst use?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When building a Union in Tableau Desktop from multiple Excel sheets, Tableau automatically adds which two generated fields to help identify the source of each row?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Table Name and Sheet Name"},{"id":"b","text":"File Paths and Row ID"},{"id":"c","text":"Sheet and File Paths"},{"id":"d","text":"Source Table and Record Number"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When Tableau creates a Union, it automatically generates two metadata fields: 'Sheet' (the name of the source worksheet) and 'File Paths' (the path of the source file). These fields allow analysts to filter or identify which source contributed each row. 'Table Name' is not an automatically generated field; 'Row ID' and 'Record Number' are not generated by Union.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/union.htm","label":"Tableau – Union Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$When building a Union in Tableau Desktop from multiple Excel sheets, Tableau automatically adds which two generated fields to help identify the source of each row?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst is working with an extract that contains 50 million rows. She wants to limit the extract to only the last 12 months of data to reduce its size. Which extract configuration option should she use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Aggregation – Roll up dates to Month"},{"id":"b","text":"Number of Rows – Incremental Refresh with a date field"},{"id":"c","text":"Filters – Add a relative date filter on the date field"},{"id":"d","text":"Hide All Unused Fields to reduce extract size"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Adding a Filter at the extract level lets the analyst specify a relative date range (e.g., last 12 months), so only qualifying rows are pulled into the .hyper file. Aggregation rolls up the granularity of date fields but does not limit rows by date range. Incremental Refresh appends new rows since the last refresh but does not retroactively remove rows outside 12 months. Hiding unused fields reduces columns, not rows.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/extracting_data.htm#configure-extract-options","label":"Tableau – Configure Extract Options"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst is working with an extract that contains 50 million rows. She wants to limit the extract to only the last 12 months of data to reduce its size. Which extract configuration option should she use?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data analyst notices that a date field imported from a CSV file is being recognized as a String data type in Tableau. What is the most appropriate way to resolve this in the Data Source pane?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a calculated field using DATEPARSE() to convert the string to a date."},{"id":"b","text":"Click the data type icon above the field in the Data Source grid and change it to Date."},{"id":"c","text":"Right-click the field in the Data pane and select 'Change Data Type > Date'."},{"id":"d","text":"Use a table calculation to cast the field as a date at the view level."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In the Data Source pane grid, each field has a data type icon (Abc, #, calendar, etc.). Clicking the icon allows the analyst to change the type directly at the source level, which is the earliest and cleanest point to fix the type. DATEPARSE() is a valid calculated-field approach if the format is non-standard, but it is secondary to fixing the type directly. Changing data type in the Data pane (option c) also works but happens after the source grid assignment. Table calculations are runtime and less efficient.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/datafields_typesandroles_datatypes.htm","label":"Tableau – Change Data Type of a Field"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data analyst notices that a date field imported from a CSV file is being recognized as a String data type in Tableau. What is the most appropriate way to resolve this in the Data Source pane?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Tableau feature allows an analyst to pivot multiple columns (e.g., Jan_Sales, Feb_Sales, Mar_Sales) into two columns—one for the period and one for the value—directly in the Data Source pane?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Data Interpreter"},{"id":"b","text":"Pivot (Columns to Rows)"},{"id":"c","text":"Union"},{"id":"d","text":"Split"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The Pivot feature in the Data Source pane allows analysts to select multiple column headers and rotate them into a two-column format: one 'Pivot Field Names' column (the period) and one 'Pivot Field Values' column (the numeric value). This restructures wide data into tall/tidy data ideal for analysis. Data Interpreter cleans formatting artifacts from Excel/Google Sheets. Union appends rows. Split breaks one column into multiple columns.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/pivot.htm","label":"Tableau – Pivot Data from Columns to Rows"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which Tableau feature allows an analyst to pivot multiple columns (e.g., Jan_Sales, Feb_Sales, Mar_Sales) into two columns—one for the period and one for the value—directly in the Data Source pane?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst creates a calculated field in Tableau using a fixed Level of Detail (LOD) expression: {FIXED [Region] : SUM([Sales])}. What does this expression compute?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The sum of Sales for each Region, regardless of any filters or dimensions in the view."},{"id":"b","text":"The sum of Sales for each Region, respecting all dimension filters applied to the view."},{"id":"c","text":"The sum of Sales for the entire table, ignoring all dimensions."},{"id":"d","text":"The average Sales per Region scoped to the current view's context."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A FIXED LOD expression computes the aggregate at the specified dimension level (Region) and ignores dimensions added to the view, making it independent of the view's level of detail. It does respect context filters and data source filters, but not regular dimension filters. INCLUDE LOD adds dimensions to the view's level of detail. EXCLUDE LOD removes dimensions. Neither option b (respects all filters) nor option c (entire table) accurately describes FIXED.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_calculatedfields_lod.htm","label":"Tableau – Level of Detail Expressions"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst creates a calculated field in Tableau using a fixed Level of Detail (LOD) expression: {FIXED [Region] : SUM([Sales])}. What does this expression compute?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau workbook is connected to a published data source on Tableau Server. The analyst wants to modify the underlying data model (add a new relationship). Where must the analyst perform this change?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Directly in the workbook's Data Source pane by editing the embedded connection."},{"id":"b","text":"On Tableau Server by navigating to the published data source and editing it there."},{"id":"c","text":"In Tableau Prep Builder by rebuilding the flow output."},{"id":"d","text":"In Tableau Desktop by downloading the data source, editing it, and republishing."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When a workbook uses a published data source, the data source is managed independently. To modify the data model (relationships, joins, etc.), the analyst must download the .tds or .tdsx from Tableau Server, open and edit it in Tableau Desktop, and then republish it. Editing directly in a workbook connected to a published source only affects a local copy; it does not modify the shared published source. Tableau Server's web authoring has limited data model editing capability for complex changes. Tableau Prep manages flow-based transformations, not Tableau data model relationships.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/publish_datasources_about.htm","label":"Tableau – Edit a Published Data Source"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau workbook is connected to a published data source on Tableau Server. The analyst wants to modify the underlying data model (add a new relationship). Where must the analyst perform this change?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst uses a Wildcard Union in Tableau Desktop to automatically union multiple CSV files stored in the same folder. Which matching pattern would correctly union all files whose names start with 'Sales_2023'?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Sales_2023%"},{"id":"b","text":"Sales_2023*"},{"id":"c","text":"Sales_2023?"},{"id":"d","text":"Sales_2023#"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau's Wildcard Union uses the asterisk (*) as the wildcard character to match any sequence of characters. Entering 'Sales_2023*' matches all files that begin with 'Sales_2023' followed by any characters. The percent sign (%) is the SQL wildcard, not used here. The question mark (?) typically matches a single character in some systems but is not the Tableau wildcard union operator. The hash (#) has no wildcard meaning in this context.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/union.htm","label":"Tableau – Union Your Data (Wildcard Union)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst uses a Wildcard Union in Tableau Desktop to automatically union multiple CSV files stored in the same folder. Which matching pattern would correctly union all files whose names start with 'Sales_2023'?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When joining two tables in Tableau Desktop, the analyst notices duplicate rows appearing in the result. The left table has one row per Order ID, but after a LEFT JOIN with a returns table that has multiple return records per Order ID, each order now appears multiple times. What is the root cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Tableau automatically deduplicates on joins, so the issue is caused by a filter."},{"id":"b","text":"The join creates a one-to-many relationship, inflating rows; use a Relationship instead to avoid row duplication."},{"id":"c","text":"The LEFT JOIN should be replaced with a FULL OUTER JOIN to remove duplicates."},{"id":"d","text":"The duplicate rows are caused by a missing primary key on the returns table."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When a physical JOIN is performed between a table with one row per Order ID and a table with multiple rows per Order ID (one-to-many), the result contains repeated rows from the left table for each matching row in the right table—this is expected join behavior and causes measure inflation. Relationships (the logical layer) avoid this problem by preserving the granularity of each table and querying them separately, aggregating before joining. FULL OUTER JOIN does not remove duplicates. A missing primary key may be a symptom but is not the root cause of the row multiplication.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/datasource_datamodel_faq.htm","label":"Tableau – When to Use Relationships vs. Joins"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$When joining two tables in Tableau Desktop, the analyst notices duplicate rows appearing in the result. The left table has one row per Order ID, but after a LEFT JOIN with a returns table that has multiple return records per Order ID, each order now appears multiple times. What is the root cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst wants to use Tableau's built-in Data Interpreter feature. For which file type is Data Interpreter available?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"PDF files only"},{"id":"b","text":"Microsoft Excel and Google Sheets files"},{"id":"c","text":"Any file type connected via ODBC"},{"id":"d","text":"Tableau Hyper extract files only"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Data Interpreter is available for Microsoft Excel (.xls, .xlsx), Google Sheets, and also .csv and .tsv files in some contexts. Its primary use case is detecting and removing formatting artifacts from spreadsheets—such as merged cells, sub-headers, and footnotes—that interfere with proper data parsing. It is not applicable to ODBC connections, PDF connectors (which have their own parsing), or .hyper extract files.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/data_interpreter.htm","label":"Tableau – Clean Data with Data Interpreter"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst wants to use Tableau's built-in Data Interpreter feature. For which file type is Data Interpreter available?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst is connecting to a large PostgreSQL database and wants Tableau to generate SQL that pushes aggregation and filtering to the database engine before returning results. Which query mode enables this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Initial SQL"},{"id":"b","text":"Custom SQL"},{"id":"c","text":"Live Connection with pushdown SQL"},{"id":"d","text":"Extract with aggregation enabled"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A Live connection in Tableau automatically generates and sends SQL (including WHERE clauses, GROUP BY, and aggregations) to the database, leveraging the database engine's processing power through query pushdown. This keeps large data on the server and only returns summarized results to Tableau. Initial SQL runs a one-time SQL statement at connection time. Custom SQL defines a specific subquery as the data source but still uses Live connection for execution. An Extract with aggregation enabled pre-aggregates data into the .hyper file, removing the ability to drill down below the aggregated level.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/performance_tips.htm","label":"Tableau – Optimize Workbook Performance"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst is connecting to a large PostgreSQL database and wants Tableau to generate SQL that pushes aggregation and filtering to the database engine before returning results. Which query mode enables this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst needs to add a parameter to dynamically control the number of top N customers shown in a view. After creating a parameter named [Top N], which step is required to make the parameter actually affect the data shown?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Drag the parameter to the Filters shelf directly."},{"id":"b","text":"Reference the parameter in a calculated field or a Top N filter and apply that to the view."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable 'Show Parameter Control' and the view updates automatically."},{"id":"d","text":"Connect the parameter to the data source using the Parameters tab in the Data Source pane."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Parameters in Tableau are dynamic values but have no effect on their own. They must be referenced in a calculated field, a filter (such as a Top N filter on a dimension), or a reference line. To implement a Top N filter, the analyst should right-click the customer dimension, select Filter, go to the Top tab, choose 'By Field', and set the value to the parameter. Simply showing the parameter control (option c) only creates the UI slider/input without wiring it to any logic. Parameters cannot be dragged to the Filters shelf directly, and there is no 'Parameters tab' in the Data Source pane.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/parameters_create.htm","label":"Tableau – Create Parameters"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
