  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst needs to add a parameter to dynamically control the number of top N customers shown in a view. After creating a parameter named [Top N], which step is required to make the parameter actually affect the data shown?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst has a date field that stores values like '03-15-2023'. She wants to convert this to a proper Tableau date. Which calculated field function correctly parses this format?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"DATE([DateField])"},{"id":"b","text":"DATEPARSE('MM-dd-yyyy', [DateField])"},{"id":"c","text":"DATETRUNC('month', [DateField])"},{"id":"d","text":"DATENAME('month', [DateField])"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$DATEPARSE() converts a string to a date using a format string. For '03-15-2023', the correct format string is 'MM-dd-yyyy' (month-day-year with dashes). DATE() attempts a basic cast but may not handle non-standard string formats reliably. DATETRUNC() truncates an existing date to a specified part (e.g., first of month) and requires the input to already be a date type. DATENAME() returns the name of a date part as a string, also requiring a date input.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/functions_functions_date.htm","label":"Tableau – DATEPARSE Function"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst has a date field that stores values like '03-15-2023'. She wants to convert this to a proper Tableau date. Which calculated field function correctly parses this format?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In Tableau's logical layer data model, two tables are related using a relationship instead of a join. Which statement correctly describes how Tableau handles NULL values that result from unmatched records between the two related tables?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Tableau drops unmatched records from both tables, behaving like an INNER JOIN."},{"id":"b","text":"Tableau performs a FULL OUTER JOIN and preserves unmatched records from both tables, showing NULLs where there is no match."},{"id":"c","text":"Tableau always performs a LEFT JOIN, keeping all records from the primary table and showing NULLs from the secondary table."},{"id":"d","text":"Tableau issues a warning and requires the analyst to define a join type before the query can run."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Relationships in Tableau's logical layer use FULL OUTER JOIN semantics at query time, ensuring that unmatched records from both tables are preserved and shown as NULLs. This is a key advantage over physical joins, which require the analyst to specify the join type (INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, FULL). Tableau dynamically generates the appropriate SQL depending on which fields from each table are used in the view, optimizing the query automatically.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/relate_tables.htm","label":"Tableau – How Relationships Differ from Joins"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In Tableau's logical layer data model, two tables are related using a relationship instead of a join. Which statement correctly describes how Tableau handles NULL values that result from unmatched records between the two related tables?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst needs to ensure that a Tableau extract refreshes with only the new rows added since the last refresh, rather than rebuilding the entire extract each time. Which option should be configured?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Full Refresh scheduled every night"},{"id":"b","text":"Incremental Refresh using a date/ID column to identify new rows"},{"id":"c","text":"Extract filter set to 'Last 1 Day'"},{"id":"d","text":"Publish the workbook with a live connection and enable server-side caching"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Incremental Refresh in Tableau allows the analyst to specify a column (typically a date or integer ID) that Tableau uses to identify and append only the rows added since the last refresh, which is much faster and less resource-intensive than a Full Refresh. A Full Refresh drops and rebuilds the entire extract each time. An extract filter limiting to 'Last 1 Day' would drop old data and is not additive. A live connection with server caching does not use an extract at all.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/extracting_refresh.htm","label":"Tableau – Refresh Extracts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst needs to ensure that a Tableau extract refreshes with only the new rows added since the last refresh, rather than rebuilding the entire extract each time. Which option should be configured?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau analyst is working with a large sales dataset and wants to identify which product subcategories fall in the bottom 10% of total revenue. Which Tableau feature should the analyst use to isolate these underperforming subcategories efficiently?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Apply a Top N filter using a calculated field that ranks subcategories by revenue"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a Condition filter on the subcategory dimension set to 'Bottom 10% by Sum of Revenue'"},{"id":"c","text":"Create a set based on subcategory using the 'Bottom' tab with condition set to 10% of the field Sum(Revenue)"},{"id":"d","text":"Use a context filter on subcategory limited to the lowest decile"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau Sets allow you to define a subset of members based on conditions. On the 'Bottom' tab of a set definition, you can specify a percentage threshold — for example, bottom 10% by a measure like Sum(Revenue). This dynamically captures all subcategories in that lowest decile. Option A (Top N filter) supports absolute N counts or percentages in the filter dialog, but Sets provide a reusable, dynamic object. Option B describes filter dialog functionality that doesn't expose a '% of field' condition natively for bottom %. Option D (context filter) is a performance optimization tool, not a selection mechanism for statistical thresholds.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/sets_create.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Create Sets"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau analyst is working with a large sales dataset and wants to identify which product subcategories fall in the bottom 10% of total revenue. Which Tableau feature should the analyst use to isolate these underperforming subcategories efficiently?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst notices that a bar chart comparing regional sales is misleading because one region has significantly more stores than others. Which analytic approach in Tableau would best normalize the comparison across regions?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Add a reference line at the overall average to provide a benchmark"},{"id":"b","text":"Create a calculated field dividing Sum(Sales) by COUNTD(Store ID) to compute average sales per store"},{"id":"c","text":"Enable the 'Synchronize Axis' option on the dual axis chart"},{"id":"d","text":"Apply a table calculation using WINDOW_AVG to smooth the values"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When comparing aggregated totals across groups of different sizes, normalization is required. Dividing Sum(Sales) by COUNTD([Store ID]) produces an average sales-per-store metric, creating a fair comparison regardless of store count. Option A adds a benchmark line but does not normalize the data values themselves. Option C is relevant to dual-axis chart scaling, not data normalization. Option D uses a window average across a table partition, which smooths trends but doesn't correct for the structural difference in store counts between regions.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_calculatedfields_create.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Create Calculated Fields"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst notices that a bar chart comparing regional sales is misleading because one region has significantly more stores than others. Which analytic approach in Tableau would best normalize the comparison across regions?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data analyst wants to show how each product category's sales contribute to the running total of all sales over the course of a year. Which type of table calculation should be applied to the Sales measure?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Percent of Total"},{"id":"b","text":"Rank"},{"id":"c","text":"Running Total"},{"id":"d","text":"Moving Average"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A Running Total table calculation accumulates values across a specified dimension (here, time), making it ideal for showing the cumulative contribution to an annual total. Percent of Total would show the proportion each period contributes to the grand total, not a running accumulation. Rank assigns a numeric rank to values rather than accumulating them. Moving Average smooths data using a rolling window, which does not represent cumulative totals.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_tablecalculations.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Table Calculations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data analyst wants to show how each product category's sales contribute to the running total of all sales over the course of a year. Which type of table calculation should be applied to the Sales measure?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In Tableau, an analyst is using a scatter plot to examine the relationship between advertising spend and sales. They want to add a linear trend line and view its R-squared value and p-value. Where are these statistics displayed?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"In the Tooltip when hovering over the trend line"},{"id":"b","text":"In the Analytics pane after right-clicking the trend line and selecting 'Describe Trend Line'"},{"id":"c","text":"In the Describe Sheet dialog accessible via the Worksheet menu"},{"id":"d","text":"In the Edit Trend Lines dialog box under 'Show Confidence Bands'"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Right-clicking on a trend line in Tableau and selecting 'Describe Trend Line' opens a dialog that displays the trend line equation, R-squared value, and p-value for statistical interpretation. Hovering the tooltip over the trend line shows the equation and R-squared, but not the full statistical detail including p-value in structured form. The Describe Sheet dialog provides field metadata, not trend statistics. The Edit Trend Lines dialog configures visual properties like confidence bands but is not the location of statistical output.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/trendlines_add.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Trend Lines in Visualizations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In Tableau, an analyst is using a scatter plot to examine the relationship between advertising spend and sales. They want to add a linear trend line and view its R-squared value and p-value. Where are these statistics displayed?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst creates a calculated field using the expression FIXED [Region] : SUM([Sales]). What does this Level of Detail (LOD) expression return?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The sum of sales aggregated at the view's current level of detail, filtered by region"},{"id":"b","text":"The sum of sales computed independently at the region level, regardless of other dimensions in the view"},{"id":"c","text":"The sum of sales at a finer granularity than the current view dimensions"},{"id":"d","text":"The sum of sales only for rows where the Region field is not null"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A FIXED LOD expression computes the aggregate at the dimension(s) specified in the expression — in this case, Region — completely independently of any other dimensions present in the view. This means no matter what other fields are on the view, the result is always the total sales per region. Option A describes a regular aggregation in the view, not a FIXED LOD. Option C describes an INCLUDE LOD behavior. Option D is incorrect; LOD expressions are not null filters.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_calculatedfields_lod.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Level of Detail Expressions"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst creates a calculated field using the expression FIXED [Region] : SUM([Sales]). What does this Level of Detail (LOD) expression return?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau analyst wants to highlight all marks in a view that exceed a dynamically adjustable sales threshold set by the user. Which combination of features best accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A parameter combined with a calculated field used as a color encoding"},{"id":"b","text":"A set action triggered by clicking a mark in the view"},{"id":"c","text":"A context filter that updates based on a slider"},{"id":"d","text":"A reference band set to the average value of sales"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Parameters allow users to input a value dynamically (e.g., via a slider or text box). A calculated field such as IF SUM([Sales]) > [Threshold Parameter] THEN 'Above' ELSE 'Below' END can then be placed on the Color shelf, visually distinguishing marks that exceed the threshold. Set actions respond to mark selections, not numeric thresholds. Context filters affect query scope, not dynamic visual highlighting. Reference bands provide visual reference lines/bands but do not change individual mark colors based on user input.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/parameters_create.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Create Parameters"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau analyst wants to highlight all marks in a view that exceed a dynamically adjustable sales threshold set by the user. Which combination of features best accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which Tableau feature allows an analyst to compare individual data values against an aggregate computed across the entire dataset, regardless of which dimensions are in the view?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"INCLUDE LOD expression"},{"id":"b","text":"EXCLUDE LOD expression"},{"id":"c","text":"FIXED LOD expression with no dimension argument"},{"id":"d","text":"A window function table calculation such as WINDOW_SUM"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A FIXED LOD expression with an empty dimension list — written as { FIXED : SUM([Sales]) } — computes the grand total across the entire dataset, unaffected by any view-level dimensions. This is commonly used to compute percentages of grand total at row level. INCLUDE LOD adds dimensions to refine aggregation below the view level. EXCLUDE LOD removes dimensions from the view-level computation. WINDOW_SUM operates on the current view's partitioned table structure, not the full dataset independently.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_calculatedfields_lod.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Level of Detail Expressions"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which Tableau feature allows an analyst to compare individual data values against an aggregate computed across the entire dataset, regardless of which dimensions are in the view?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst is building a view that compares this year's monthly sales to the same month in the previous year. Which table calculation function is most appropriate for this year-over-year comparison?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"WINDOW_AVG(SUM([Sales]), -12, 0)"},{"id":"b","text":"LOOKUP(SUM([Sales]), -12)"},{"id":"c","text":"RUNNING_SUM(SUM([Sales]))"},{"id":"d","text":"RANK(SUM([Sales]))"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$LOOKUP(expression, offset) retrieves the value of an expression in a different row relative to the current row. With monthly data, an offset of -12 returns the value from 12 months prior — exactly the prior year's same month — enabling year-over-year comparisons. WINDOW_AVG with a -12 offset computes an average over the trailing 12-month window, not a direct prior-year lookup. RUNNING_SUM accumulates values and is not useful for YoY comparison. RANK assigns ordinal positions, not comparative values.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/functions_functions_tablecalculation.htm#LOOKUP","label":"Tableau Help – LOOKUP Function"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst is building a view that compares this year's monthly sales to the same month in the previous year. Which table calculation function is most appropriate for this year-over-year comparison?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In Tableau, what is the primary purpose of the Analytics pane?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"To manage data source connections and blending relationships"},{"id":"b","text":"To drag and drop analytic objects such as reference lines, trend lines, forecasts, and cluster models onto a view"},{"id":"c","text":"To write and validate custom calculated fields and LOD expressions"},{"id":"d","text":"To configure filter interactions between worksheets in a dashboard"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The Analytics pane in Tableau (accessed by clicking the Analytics tab in the left sidebar) provides drag-and-drop access to analytical overlays including reference lines, reference bands, trend lines, forecasts, box plots, average lines, and cluster analysis. These can be dragged directly onto a view. Managing data source connections is done in the Data Source tab. Calculated fields are authored via the calculated field editor, not the Analytics pane. Dashboard filter interactions are configured via the dashboard action dialogs.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/analytics_pane.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Analytics Pane"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In Tableau, what is the primary purpose of the Analytics pane?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau analyst wants to determine whether a time-series of weekly revenue has a statistically meaningful upward trend. Which built-in Tableau capability should the analyst use first?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable clustering on the time dimension to identify distinct trend groups"},{"id":"b","text":"Add a linear trend line via the Analytics pane and review the p-value"},{"id":"c","text":"Use a Running Total table calculation and observe whether it increases over time"},{"id":"d","text":"Apply a WINDOW_AVG calculation with a 4-week window to smooth the data"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau's built-in trend line feature uses statistical regression and produces a p-value which indicates whether the observed trend is statistically significant. A p-value below the significance threshold (commonly 0.05) supports the conclusion of a meaningful trend. Clustering groups marks by similarity across measures, not along a time axis for trend detection. A Running Total increasing over time simply reflects cumulative growth, not statistical significance. A moving average smooths noise but does not provide a significance test.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/trendlines_add.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Trend Lines in Visualizations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau analyst wants to determine whether a time-series of weekly revenue has a statistically meaningful upward trend. Which built-in Tableau capability should the analyst use first?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst has a dataset with millions of rows and needs to sample a representative subset for exploratory visual analysis in Tableau without modifying the underlying data source. Which Tableau feature enables this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Data Extract with a row limit set in the Extract dialog"},{"id":"b","text":"The 'Sample' data connection option available in the Data Source tab"},{"id":"c","text":"Enabling 'Sampling' in View > Page Controls"},{"id":"d","text":"Applying a context filter limiting rows to a random percentage"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When creating a Tableau Extract (.hyper), the Extract dialog provides an option to limit the number of rows extracted, allowing the analyst to work with a manageable sample while keeping the full dataset intact in the source. Tableau does not natively have a 'Sample' data connection option separate from extract settings. There is no 'Sampling' option under Page Controls. While a context filter can reduce the dataset in the view, it doesn't create a statistical sample and requires additional logic to randomize.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/extracting_data.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Extract Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
