  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When building a geographic map in Tableau, an analyst notices that several city names are unrecognized and displayed as unknown locations. What is the MOST direct way to resolve this issue within Tableau Desktop?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Convert the geographic field to a string dimension and use it as a label"},{"id":"b","text":"Edit the geographic role of the field and use 'Edit Locations' to manually map unknown values"},{"id":"c","text":"Create a calculated field that concatenates latitude and longitude strings"},{"id":"d","text":"Replace the geographic field with a Mapbox custom map layer"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau's 'Edit Locations' dialog (accessible by right-clicking the field or via the map indicator) lets analysts manually match unrecognized place names to known geographic entries, or specify country/state context that helps disambiguation. Converting to a string loses geographic functionality. Concatenating lat/long strings is not a valid geocoding approach. Replacing with a Mapbox layer changes the background tile but does not resolve geocoding of data points.$patch$, $patch$Create Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/maps_editlocation.htm","label":"Tableau – Correct Unrecognized Locations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
