         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Scatter plot"},{"id":"b","text":"Treemap"},{"id":"c","text":"Line chart"},{"id":"d","text":"Histogram"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Line chart: trends over continuous (date) axis.' When a date dimension and one measure are selected, Tableau's Show Me panel bolds (recommends) a line chart because a continuous date axis paired with a single measure is the canonical use case for trend analysis. A scatter plot requires two measures. A treemap is for hierarchical parts-of-a-whole and needs a dimension plus a measure but is not the recommended chart for date-based data. A histogram requires a single measure placed in bins, not a date dimension.$patch$, $patch$Create Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/buildauto_showme.htm","label":"Tableau — Show Me: Change the Chart Type"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
