INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In Tableau, what is the primary purpose of promoting a filter to a 'Context Filter'?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"To create a subset of data that all other filters, Top N filters, and computed sets evaluate against"},{"id":"b","text":"To apply a filter only to a specific worksheet and not to related dashboards"},{"id":"c","text":"To allow the filter to be shared across multiple data sources in the same workbook"},{"id":"d","text":"To make the filter visible to all users who access the published view"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Context filters run first and create a temporary table of the filtered data. All subsequent dimension filters, measure filters, and Top N/Bottom N conditions operate on that temporary context table rather than the full dataset. This is critical for correct Top N behavior. A worksheet-scoped filter is managed through worksheet scope settings. Cross-data-source filtering uses data blending or relationships. Filter visibility is controlled through dashboard actions and user permissions.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/filtering_context.htm","label":"Tableau – Context Filters"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In Tableau, what is the primary purpose of promoting a filter to a 'Context Filter'?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst is reviewing a scatter plot of [Discount] vs. [Profit] and notices an unexpected cluster of high-discount, negative-profit marks. Which Tableau analytic feature would BEST help the analyst statistically characterize the linear relationship between these two measures?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Adding a linear trend line via the Analytics pane"},{"id":"b","text":"Applying a reference band between the two axes"},{"id":"c","text":"Creating a histogram of the Discount field"},{"id":"d","text":"Adding a box plot for the Profit measure"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A linear trend line in Tableau's Analytics pane fits a regression line to the scatter plot and provides R-squared, p-value, and slope/intercept statistics on hover, which directly characterizes the linear relationship between two continuous measures. A reference band highlights a value range but provides no regression statistics. A histogram shows distribution of one measure. A box plot shows distribution and outliers for one measure but does not capture the bivariate relationship.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/trendlines_add.htm","label":"Tableau – Add Trend Lines to a Visualization"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
