INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When using Tableau's 'Explain Data' feature on a mark in a view, what type of insight does Tableau automatically surface?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Statistical explanations of why a specific mark's value may be unusual, including contributing factors from other fields"},{"id":"b","text":"A list of all calculated fields used to generate the mark"},{"id":"c","text":"The underlying SQL query executed to return the mark's data"},{"id":"d","text":"Recommendations for alternative chart types that could display the same data"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Explain Data uses statistical analysis to automatically identify factors that may explain why a particular mark's value is notable (e.g., higher or lower than expected). It surfaces explanations like correlated dimensions, outliers, and driving fields. It does not list calculated fields used, display underlying SQL (that is the 'View Data' or performance recorder feature), or recommend chart types (that is the Show Me panel).$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/explain_data_basics.htm","label":"Tableau – Explain Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$When using Tableau's 'Explain Data' feature on a mark in a view, what type of insight does Tableau automatically surface?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst needs to display a running total of [Revenue] that resets at the start of each [Year]. Which configuration of a Running Sum table calculation achieves this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Set Compute Using to 'Table (across)' and add [Year] as a Restarting Every dimension"},{"id":"b","text":"Set Compute Using to 'Table (down)' with no restarting dimension"},{"id":"c","text":"Use a FIXED LOD on [Year] instead of a table calculation"},{"id":"d","text":"Apply a context filter for each year and create separate sheets"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Running Sum table calculations support a 'Restarting Every' option that resets the accumulation when the specified dimension changes. Setting Compute Using to 'Table (across)' and selecting [Year] as the Restarting Every field causes the running total to restart at each new year. Computing down with no restart would accumulate across all years. A FIXED LOD does not provide a running accumulation within a period. Creating separate sheets is a manual workaround, not a dynamic calculation.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_tablecalculations_definebasic_runningtotal.htm","label":"Tableau – Running Total Table Calculation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst needs to display a running total of [Revenue] that resets at the start of each [Year]. Which configuration of a Running Sum table calculation achieves this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which of the following correctly describes the difference between a Tableau 'Group' and a Tableau 'Set'?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A Group statically combines members into named buckets; a Set can be dynamic and update based on conditions or top/bottom filters"},{"id":"b","text":"A Group can only be created on measures; a Set can only be created on dimensions"},{"id":"c","text":"A Group supports combined membership from two fields; a Set is limited to one field"},{"id":"d","text":"A Set is used exclusively for hierarchical drill-down; a Group is used for filtering"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Groups in Tableau combine selected dimension members into a manually defined, named category (static). Sets can be static (manually chosen members) or dynamic (condition-based or top/bottom N), automatically updating when data changes. Both Groups and Sets operate on dimensions, not measures. Sets can be combined (union/intersection/difference) across two sets from the same field. Neither is exclusively for drill-down or filtering.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/sortgroup_groups_creating.htm","label":"Tableau – Groups vs Sets"},{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/sortgroup_sets_create.htm","label":"Tableau – Create Sets"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which of the following correctly describes the difference between a Tableau 'Group' and a Tableau 'Set'?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst notices that a measure filter on [Profit] is not correctly limiting data when a Top 10 [Customer Name] filter is also applied. The Top 10 filter is returning customers based on all data, not just the profitable ones. What is the MOST efficient fix?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Promote the Profit measure filter to a context filter so the Top 10 filter evaluates against filtered data"},{"id":"b","text":"Change the Top 10 filter to use a FIXED LOD expression"},{"id":"c","text":"Remove the Profit filter and use a calculated field that excludes negative profit inside the Top 10 logic"},{"id":"d","text":"Apply the Profit filter as a table calculation filter instead"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau applies filters in a specific order: context filters → data source filters → dimension filters → measure filters → table calc filters. Top N filters are computed before measure filters by default, so they evaluate against full data. Promoting the Profit filter to a context filter moves it earlier in the order of operations, ensuring the Top 10 is computed only from profitable rows. Changing to a FIXED LOD would ignore the filter. Adding the condition to the Top N formula is more complex and less maintainable. Table calculation filters run last, not before Top N.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/order_of_operations.htm","label":"Tableau – Order of Operations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst notices that a measure filter on [Profit] is not correctly limiting data when a Top 10 [Customer Name] filter is also applied. The Top 10 filter is returning customers based on all data, not just the profitable ones. What is the MOST efficient fix?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau calculated field uses `ZN([Profit])`. What does ZN do?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Replaces NULL values with zero, leaving non-NULL values unchanged"},{"id":"b","text":"Converts all negative profit values to zero"},{"id":"c","text":"Returns zero if profit is less than a threshold, otherwise returns the profit value"},{"id":"d","text":"Rounds the profit value to the nearest integer"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$ZN(expression) is a Tableau utility function that returns zero when the expression evaluates to NULL, and returns the expression's value otherwise. It is equivalent to IFNULL([Profit], 0). It does not affect negative values, apply threshold logic, or round values. It is commonly used to prevent NULL propagation in arithmetic calculations.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/functions_functions_logical.htm","label":"Tableau – ZN Function"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau calculated field uses `ZN([Profit])`. What does ZN do?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$In Tableau, which analytic object from the Analytics pane can be used to highlight the range between two percentile values for a continuous measure on a view?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Reference Band"},{"id":"b","text":"Reference Line"},{"id":"c","text":"Box Plot"},{"id":"d","text":"Distribution Band"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A Distribution Band in Tableau's Analytics pane draws bands based on statistical distributions, including percentile ranges (e.g., the band between the 25th and 75th percentile). A Reference Line marks a single value. A Reference Band marks the range between two fixed or computed values but does not natively compute percentile distributions. A Box Plot is a chart type showing quartile distribution, not an overlay band on an existing chart.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/reference_lines.htm","label":"Tableau – Add Reference Lines, Bands, Distributions, and Box Plots"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$In Tableau, which analytic object from the Analytics pane can be used to highlight the range between two percentile values for a continuous measure on a view?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst wants to show year-over-year percentage change in quarterly sales. The view has [Quarter of Order Date] on Columns and SUM([Sales]) on Rows. Which table calculation type should be applied to SUM([Sales])?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Percent Difference From with Previous period, computed across the Table (down) direction"},{"id":"b","text":"Running Total computed across the Table (across) direction"},{"id":"c","text":"Percent of Total computed across the entire Table"},{"id":"d","text":"Rank computed using a custom calculation"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Percent Difference From calculates ((current - previous) / previous) × 100. Setting it to compare to the 'Previous' period computes the quarter-over-quarter change; to get year-over-year change for the same quarter, the analyst would set the offset to compare against the same quarter of the prior year (Previous with an offset). Computing Table (down) means the calculation moves down the column, which is correct when years are arranged down rows. Running Total accumulates values, not differences. Percent of Total shows share of a whole. Rank assigns ordinal positions.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_tablecalculations_definebasic_percentdifference.htm","label":"Tableau – Percent Difference Table Calculation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst wants to show year-over-year percentage change in quarterly sales. The view has [Quarter of Order Date] on Columns and SUM([Sales]) on Rows. Which table calculation type should be applied to SUM([Sales])?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau analyst uses `INCLUDE [Sub-Category] : SUM([Sales])` as a calculated field in a view that only has [Category] in the level of detail. What is the effect of the INCLUDE LOD expression?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"It computes SUM(Sales) at the Category + Sub-Category level and aggregates those values up to the Category level in the view"},{"id":"b","text":"It computes SUM(Sales) only at the Sub-Category level and ignores Category entirely"},{"id":"c","text":"It returns the same result as SUM(Sales) because Category already covers Sub-Category"},{"id":"d","text":"It raises an error because INCLUDE cannot reference a lower level of detail than the view"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$INCLUDE adds the specified dimension(s) to the view's level of detail for the calculation. With [Category] in the view and INCLUDE [Sub-Category], the LOD expression computes SUM(Sales) at the Category + Sub-Category grain, then those sub-values are aggregated (typically averaged) in the view back up to the Category level. This is useful for computing per-sub-category averages in a category-level view. It does not ignore Category, and it does not produce an error.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_calculatedfields_lod_include.htm","label":"Tableau – INCLUDE Level of Detail Expressions"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau analyst uses `INCLUDE [Sub-Category] : SUM([Sales])` as a calculated field in a view that only has [Category] in the level of detail. What is the effect of the INCLUDE LOD expression?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Which of the following statements about Tableau's cluster analysis feature is TRUE?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Tableau uses a k-means algorithm to group marks into clusters based on selected measures"},{"id":"b","text":"Clusters in Tableau are determined using a hierarchical agglomerative algorithm"},{"id":"c","text":"Clusters can be created on dimension fields only, not on measure fields"},{"id":"d","text":"Clusters automatically determine the optimal number of groups using silhouette scoring displayed in the UI"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau's built-in clustering (available via the Analytics pane) uses the k-means algorithm, where the user specifies the number of clusters k and Tableau partitions the marks based on selected measures. It is not hierarchical/agglomerative. Clustering requires measure fields as inputs, not dimensions. While Tableau uses internal heuristics for initial centroids, it does not surface silhouette scores in the UI; the user manually selects k.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/clustering.htm","label":"Tableau – How Clustering Works"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Which of the following statements about Tableau's cluster analysis feature is TRUE?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst has a view with [Region] on Rows and SUM([Sales]) on Columns. They want to add a horizontal line showing the average SUM(Sales) across all regions. Where in Tableau Desktop should the analyst go to add this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Drag 'Average Line' from the Analytics pane onto the view at the 'Table' scope"},{"id":"b","text":"Right-click the SUM(Sales) axis and select 'Add Reference Line'"},{"id":"c","text":"Create a calculated field with WINDOW_AVG and place it on the Detail shelf"},{"id":"d","text":"Use the Format menu to add a line at the average value"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau's Analytics pane contains drag-and-drop analytic objects including Average Line, which can be scoped at the Table, Pane, or Cell level. Dragging 'Average Line' to the 'Table' scope adds a single horizontal reference line at the overall average of SUM(Sales) across all regions. Right-clicking the axis (option B) also works technically, but the Analytics pane is the primary intended workflow. A WINDOW_AVG calculated field placed on Detail would not visually draw a line. The Format menu controls visual formatting, not analytic overlays.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/analytics_pane.htm","label":"Tableau – Analytics Pane Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst has a view with [Region] on Rows and SUM([Sales]) on Columns. They want to add a horizontal line showing the average SUM(Sales) across all regions. Where in Tableau Desktop should the analyst go to add this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A view shows SUM([Profit]) broken down by [State]. The analyst wants to highlight only the states where Profit is BELOW zero using a different color. Which approach is MOST efficient in Tableau?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a calculated field `IF SUM([Profit]) < 0 THEN 'Negative' ELSE 'Positive' END` and place it on the Color shelf"},{"id":"b","text":"Add a reference line at zero and manually change each bar color below the line"},{"id":"c","text":"Apply a filter to exclude states where Profit >= 0"},{"id":"d","text":"Use the Analytics pane to add a Box Plot that highlights outliers below zero"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Creating a calculated field that categorizes marks as 'Negative' or 'Positive' based on whether SUM(Profit) is below zero, and placing it on the Color shelf, is the most efficient and dynamic approach. Tableau will automatically assign different colors to the two categories, and the view will update as data changes. Manually changing each bar is tedious and not dynamic. Applying a filter removes the states rather than highlighting them. A Box Plot is a different visualization type and does not color-highlight individual bars in a bar chart.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_calculatedfields_create.htm","label":"Tableau – Color Encoding with Calculated Fields"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A view shows SUM([Profit]) broken down by [State]. The analyst wants to highlight only the states where Profit is BELOW zero using a different color. Which approach is MOST efficient in Tableau?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$What does the Tableau EXCLUDE LOD expression `{EXCLUDE [Month] : SUM([Sales])}` return when [Month] is in the view?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The SUM of Sales aggregated at the level of detail of the view minus the [Month] dimension"},{"id":"b","text":"The SUM of Sales only for the current month in the view"},{"id":"c","text":"NULL for every mark, because Month cannot be excluded"},{"id":"d","text":"The SUM of Sales at the full dataset level, equivalent to a grand total"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$EXCLUDE removes the named dimension(s) from the view's level of detail when computing the expression. If the view has [Region] and [Month], then `{EXCLUDE [Month] : SUM([Sales])}` computes SUM(Sales) at the [Region] level (Month excluded). Each row in the view for a given Region will show the same value: the Region-level total. This is useful for computing % of subtotal within a higher-level aggregate. It does not return NULL, and it is not a grand total unless [Month] is the only dimension.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_calculatedfields_lod_exclude.htm","label":"Tableau – EXCLUDE Level of Detail Expressions"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$What does the Tableau EXCLUDE LOD expression `{EXCLUDE [Month] : SUM([Sales])}` return when [Month] is in the view?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst wants to use forecasting in Tableau. The view contains monthly order counts over two years. After enabling the forecast from the Analytics pane, which model does Tableau use by default?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Exponential smoothing (ETS) model, with Tableau automatically selecting the best trend and seasonality parameters"},{"id":"b","text":"ARIMA model with auto-selected p, d, q parameters"},{"id":"c","text":"Linear regression extrapolated forward from all historical data points"},{"id":"d","text":"Simple moving average with a 3-period window"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau's built-in forecasting uses an exponential smoothing (ETS – Error, Trend, Seasonality) model. Tableau automatically evaluates multiple ETS model configurations and selects the best fit based on AIC (Akaike Information Criterion). It is not ARIMA, a simple linear regression, or a moving average. The automatic model selection makes it accessible without requiring the analyst to manually specify parameters.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/forecast_how_it_works.htm","label":"Tableau – How Forecasting Works"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst wants to use forecasting in Tableau. The view contains monthly order counts over two years. After enabling the forecast from the Analytics pane, which model does Tableau use by default?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau calculated field is written as: `IF [Region] = 'West' AND SUM([Sales]) > 100000 THEN 'High West' ELSE 'Other' END`. This field is placed on the Color shelf. What problem will Tableau report?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cannot mix aggregate and non-aggregate comparisons in the same formula"},{"id":"b","text":"IF statements are not allowed in calculated fields used on the Color shelf"},{"id":"c","text":"The string 'West' cannot be compared directly to a dimension field"},{"id":"d","text":"SUM([Sales]) cannot be used in an IF statement"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau requires that calculated fields be either entirely aggregate or entirely non-aggregate (row-level). Mixing `[Region]` (a non-aggregate dimension comparison) with `SUM([Sales])` (an aggregate function) in the same expression causes a 'cannot mix aggregate and non-aggregate' error. The fix is to make [Region] an aggregate (e.g., `MIN([Region])`) or restructure the logic. IF statements are fully valid in calculated fields. String comparison to a dimension is valid. SUM can be used inside IF.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_aggregation.htm","label":"Tableau – Aggregate and Non-Aggregate Mixing Error"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau calculated field is written as: `IF [Region] = 'West' AND SUM([Sales]) > 100000 THEN 'High West' ELSE 'Other' END`. This field is placed on the Color shelf. What problem will Tableau report?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst has a Tableau view with quarterly sales data. They add a forecast and then view the 'Describe Forecast' dialog. Which of the following metrics can be found in this dialog?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The forecast model type, quality metrics (RMSE, MAE), and seasonal length identified"},{"id":"b","text":"The underlying SQL query used to retrieve the forecast data"},{"id":"c","text":"A comparison of the forecast to a benchmark index chosen by the user"},{"id":"d","text":"The list of dimension filters applied before forecasting"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The 'Describe Forecast' dialog in Tableau surfaces detailed information about the selected forecast model, including the ETS model variant chosen, quality measures such as RMSE (Root Mean Square Error) and MAE (Mean Absolute Error), the seasonal length detected, and the initial smoothing values. It does not display underlying SQL queries, allow user-defined benchmark comparisons, or list dimension filters. This dialog helps analysts assess forecast reliability.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/forecast_describe.htm","label":"Tableau – Forecast Descriptions and Results"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
