         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Live connection, so the data is always current"},{"id":"b","text":"Extract connection (.hyper file), which stores an in-memory snapshot for faster queries"},{"id":"c","text":"Cross-database join connection, which parallelizes queries"},{"id":"d","text":"Web Data Connector, which caches results locally"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Extract (.hyper file, in-memory snapshot, faster, supports incremental refresh).' Switching to an Extract connection creates a .hyper file that Tableau queries in-memory, dramatically improving performance over a Live connection that queries the source database in real time. A cross-database join is about joining across different connections, not a performance optimization strategy. Web Data Connectors are a connector type, not a performance mode.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/extracting_data.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Extract Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
