         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Relationship"},{"id":"b","text":"Inner Join"},{"id":"c","text":"Union"},{"id":"d","text":"Data Blend"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Unions: combine tables with the same columns.' A Union stacks rows from tables that share the same column structure, making it the correct choice here. A Relationship links tables on a key but does not stack rows. A Join combines columns side-by-side and can produce duplicates or missing rows depending on type. Data Blending operates across separate connections at the view level, not at the data source page.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
