         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Inner Join"},{"id":"b","text":"Right Join"},{"id":"c","text":"Left Join"},{"id":"d","text":"Full Outer Join"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material lists join types: 'Joins (physical layer): Inner, Left, Right, Full Outer.' A Left Join returns all rows from the left (primary) table — Orders in this case — and matched rows from the right table (Returns), filling unmatched returns columns with NULL. An Inner Join would exclude Orders with no returns. A Right Join would keep all Returns rows, dropping Orders with no returns. A Full Outer Join keeps all rows from both sides, which is more than needed and could inflate row counts.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/joining_tables.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Join Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
