  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When using Tableau Desktop's Relationships model (logical layer) instead of physical-layer joins, what is the key behavioral difference that makes Relationships preferable for multi-table analyses?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Relationships always perform a Full Outer Join between all tables, ensuring no data is lost"},{"id":"b","text":"Relationships preserve each table's context and perform automatic appropriate aggregation at query time, avoiding row duplication"},{"id":"c","text":"Relationships convert all measures to discrete fields to prevent double-counting"},{"id":"d","text":"Relationships replace the need for calculated fields by auto-computing all possible aggregations"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Relationships (new model): logical layer connecting tables; preserves context, automatic aggregation.' Unlike physical joins that merge tables into a single flat table (risking row duplication at different granularities), Relationships let Tableau query each table at the appropriate grain and join results at the level of detail needed by the view. They do not force a Full Outer Join, do not change measure pill types, and do not replace calculated fields.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/relate_tables.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Relate Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
