         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Add a Top 10 filter on the Customer Name field, then sort the bar chart by Sum(Sales) in descending order"},{"id":"b","text":"Add a Condition filter on Customer Name set to Sum(Sales) > 0, then manually drag bars to reorder"},{"id":"c","text":"Create a calculated field ranking customers and use a data source filter to limit rows to 10"},{"id":"d","text":"Use a context filter on Customer Name, then add a Top filter on Sales for the top 10 by average"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The Top tab within the Filter dialog for a dimension (Customer Name) allows you to filter to the top N members by a measure (Sum of Sales). Combining this with a descending sort on the axis produces the correct ranked bar chart. Option B does not limit to top 10 and manual reordering is not reliable. Option C uses a workaround that adds unnecessary complexity. Option D uses a context filter incorrectly and filters by average rather than sum.$patch$, $patch$Create Content$patch$,
