         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a calculated field that returns a string ('Above Target' or 'Below Target'), place it on the Color shelf, then manually assign green and red to each string value"},{"id":"b","text":"Place the Profit measure on the Color shelf and use a stepped color palette with two steps"},{"id":"c","text":"Write a Level of Detail expression that computes profit and drag it to the Size shelf"},{"id":"d","text":"Use a reference line set at $50,000 and enable the 'Color above/below' option on the reference line dialog"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Creating a string calculated field (e.g., IF SUM([Profit]) > 50000 THEN 'Above Target' ELSE 'Below Target' END) and placing it on Color gives full manual control over which color maps to each category. Option B using a continuous measure on Color does not allow precise two-color breakpoints easily. Option C misuses LOD expressions and the Size shelf. Option D—reference lines do not have a 'Color above/below' mark option for the shape mark itself.$patch$, $patch$Create Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/viewparts_marks_markproperties_color.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Color Encoding"},{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/calculations_calculatedfields_create.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Create a Calculated Field"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
