  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau developer has built a worksheet with a geographic map using a State dimension. They now want to add a second layer to the map that shows store-level data using Latitude and Longitude fields from a different data source. Which Tableau feature enables this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Map Layers pane with a dual-axis map using a blended data source"},{"id":"b","text":"A Tableau Map Layer added via the Map menu → Map Layers option pointing to a WMS server"},{"id":"c","text":"Dual-axis mapping by placing both the auto-generated Latitude and a custom Latitude field on the Rows shelf and synchronizing axes"},{"id":"d","text":"A Layout Container on the dashboard placed over the original map"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau supports dual-axis maps by placing two Latitude fields on the Rows shelf (the auto-generated one and a second custom Latitude) and two Longitude fields on Columns, then synchronizing axes. This overlays two independent mark layers on the same map—one per data source or level of detail. Option A describes a general concept loosely but the mechanism is dual-axis, not a 'Map Layers pane with blend.' Option B adds external tile layers (WMS), not additional data marks. Option D uses a dashboard layout container, which is a workaround, not a native map layer.$patch$, $patch$Create Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/maps_dualaxis.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Dual-Axis Maps"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
