         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The linear model explains a large proportion of the variance in the dependent variable"},{"id":"b","text":"The linear model explains very little of the variance, meaning a weak linear relationship exists"},{"id":"c","text":"The data has a perfect non-linear relationship that Tableau cannot model"},{"id":"d","text":"The p-value is statistically significant and the model should be trusted"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$R-squared (coefficient of determination) measures the proportion of variance in the dependent variable explained by the model. A low R-squared (close to 0) means the linear trend line fits the data poorly and the two measures have a weak linear relationship. Option (a) describes a high R-squared, not a low one. Option (c) is a possible interpretation but is not what R-squared directly states. Option (d) confuses R-squared with p-value; a low R-squared does not indicate statistical significance.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/trendlines_add.htm","label":"Tableau – Trend Lines in Tableau"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
