  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A calculated field uses the expression: IIF(ISNULL([Discount]), 0, [Discount]). Which built-in function could replace this expression entirely with a more concise equivalent?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"IFNULL([Discount], 0)"},{"id":"b","text":"ZN([Discount])"},{"id":"c","text":"NOT ISNULL([Discount])"},{"id":"d","text":"NULLIF([Discount], 0)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$ZN(expression) returns the expression value if it is not null, and zero if it is null — exactly equivalent to IIF(ISNULL(x), 0, x). IFNULL(x, 0) is also semantically equivalent (option a), but ZN is the most concise purpose-built function for replacing nulls with zero. Both a and b are functionally correct, but ZN is the single most concise built-in shorthand. The source lists both IFNULL and ZN under Logical functions.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/functions_functions_logical.htm","label":"Tableau Logical Functions"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
