  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is creating a combo chart that overlays monthly website visits (bars) with a monthly conversion rate (line). The two measures have very different numeric scales. What step is MOST important to ensure the chart is interpreted correctly?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Apply a table calculation to normalize both measures to the same scale before creating the dual axis."},{"id":"b","text":"Use the Color mark to differentiate the two measures."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a dual axis and synchronize the axes only when the two measures share a comparable scale; otherwise leave them independent."},{"id":"d","text":"Place both measures on Rows instead of using a dual axis."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source states: 'Dual axis: two measures on same x-axis with separate y-scales; synchronize axis if comparable scales.' Since the two measures have very different scales, synchronizing them would distort one of the series. Leaving the axes independent while using a dual-axis layout is the correct approach. Using Color alone (B) does not resolve scale differences. Normalizing via table calculation (A) changes the data rather than the display. Placing both on Rows (D) creates separate panes, not a combo chart.$patch$, $patch$Create Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/multiple_measures.htm","label":"Tableau – Dual Axis Charts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
