INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company's security policy requires that the Finance team's workbooks on Tableau Server inherit no permissions from the parent project. A Tableau Site Administrator wants to ensure Finance users can view Finance workbooks but cannot download them. Which approach correctly implements this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Set the project permission template to 'All', which grants every capability including View but automatically blocks Download."},{"id":"b","text":"Use the 'Custom' permission template on the Finance project to explicitly grant View and deny Download for the Finance user group, then lock the project permissions."},{"id":"c","text":"Assign the Finance users the Viewer site role; Viewer automatically prevents all downloads across every project."},{"id":"d","text":"Remove the Finance users from the project and rely on workbook-level permissions set to 'None'."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states permissions include individual capabilities such as 'View, Interact, Download, Edit, Save, Set Permissions, Delete' and that 'Inherited permissions from project [apply] unless overridden,' with templates of 'All, None, Custom.' Using a Custom template lets the administrator selectively grant View while denying Download, and locking the project prevents individual workbooks from overriding those settings. Option A ('All' template) grants all capabilities including Download, which violates policy. Option C is incorrect because the Viewer site role does restrict some actions but does not universally block downloads for all content types regardless of project settings; granular capability control is still required. Option D would prevent Finance users from seeing the workbooks at all.$patch$, $patch$Publish and Manage Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/server/en-us/permissions.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Permissions"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company's security policy requires that the Finance team's workbooks on Tableau Server inherit no permissions from the parent project. A Tableau Site Administrator wants to ensure Finance users can view Finance workbooks but cannot download them. Which approach correctly implements this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A development team wants to embed a Tableau Cloud dashboard into an internal web portal so that authenticated employees can interact with it without seeing a separate Tableau login prompt. The team plans to use JSON Web Tokens (JWTs) for authentication. Which Tableau feature supports this embedding scenario?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Tableau Catalog lineage view"},{"id":"b","text":"Tableau Bridge agent"},{"id":"c","text":"Connected apps with JWT authentication via the Tableau Embedding API v3"},{"id":"d","text":"Tableau Prep Conductor flow schedule"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Embed dashboards via iframe or JavaScript API on websites. Tableau Embedding API v3 for programmatic interaction. Connected apps / JWT auth for embedded viewing.' Connected apps allow an external application to pass a signed JWT to Tableau Cloud, enabling seamless single-sign-on for embedded dashboards so users never see a Tableau login prompt. Tableau Catalog lineage tracks asset dependencies. Tableau Bridge connects on-premises data to Tableau Cloud. Tableau Prep Conductor schedules data preparation flows. None of those address embedding authentication.$patch$, $patch$Publish and Manage Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/online/en-us/connected_apps.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Use Connected Apps for Application Integration"},{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/api/embedding_api/en-us/index.html","label":"Tableau Embedding API v3 Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A development team wants to embed a Tableau Cloud dashboard into an internal web portal so that authenticated employees can interact with it without seeing a separate Tableau login prompt. The team plans to use JSON Web Tokens (JWTs) for authentication. Which Tableau feature supports this embedding scenario?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau Server administrator notices that a shared data source used by 14 workbooks may contain inaccurate data pending an upstream fix. The administrator wants to alert all content consumers immediately without unpublishing the data source. Which Tableau feature provides this capability?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Subscription email to all consumers on a daily schedule"},{"id":"b","text":"Data quality warning placed on the data source via Tableau Catalog"},{"id":"c","text":"Revoking the View capability on the data source for all users until the fix is applied"},{"id":"d","text":"Pausing the extract refresh schedule for the data source"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that Tableau Catalog (part of the Data Management add-on) provides 'Data quality warnings on data sources.' A data quality warning surfaces a visible banner to any user who opens a workbook or view that depends on the flagged data source, immediately communicating the data reliability issue without removing access. Option A sends a scheduled email snapshot but does not actively warn users at point of consumption and cannot be sent immediately to all consumers on demand. Option C removes access entirely, which is more disruptive than a warning. Option D stops refreshes but gives no in-product signal to consumers about the data quality problem.$patch$, $patch$Publish and Manage Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/server/en-us/dm_catalog_quality_warn.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Tableau Catalog – Data Quality Warnings"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
