INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data governance team needs to identify which Tableau workbooks and dashboards are consuming a specific published data source that was recently found to contain data quality issues. They also want to flag the data source so that all consumers see a warning before using it. Which Tableau capability addresses both of these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Tableau Prep Conductor — schedule the cleansing flow and notify downstream workbooks automatically."},{"id":"b","text":"Tableau Catalog — use lineage to view upstream/downstream dependencies and set a data quality warning on the data source."},{"id":"c","text":"Tableau Pulse — subscribe governance team members to an AI digest that surfaces data quality anomalies."},{"id":"d","text":"Tableau Server subscriptions — send a scheduled snapshot of the data source to all workbook owners."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material directly describes Tableau Catalog as the feature that enables both requirements: 'Lineage: see upstream/downstream dependencies' (to identify which workbooks consume the data source) and 'Data quality warnings on data sources' (to flag the data source so consumers are notified). Tableau Catalog is part of the Data Management add-on. Prep Conductor schedules flows but does not surface downstream dependency maps or quality warnings. Tableau Pulse provides AI-driven personalized insights, not lineage tracking or manual quality warnings. Subscriptions send scheduled snapshots but cannot display dependency graphs or attach quality warning labels.$patch$, $patch$Publish and Manage Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/server/en-us/dm_catalog_overview.htm","label":"Tableau Catalog Overview — Tableau Help"},{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/server/en-us/dm_dqw.htm","label":"Data Quality Warnings — Tableau Help"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data governance team needs to identify which Tableau workbooks and dashboards are consuming a specific published data source that was recently found to contain data quality issues. They also want to flag the data source so that all consumers see a warning before using it. Which Tableau capability addresses both of these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau Site Administrator is publishing a workbook to Tableau Server and must embed database credentials so that all viewers see live data without being prompted to log in to the database. During the publish dialog, which option accomplishes this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Select 'Prompt user' so each viewer enters their own database credentials at runtime."},{"id":"b","text":"Select 'Embed credentials for live connections' to store the credentials with the published workbook."},{"id":"c","text":"Convert the live connection to an extract so credentials are no longer required at all."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable Tableau Bridge to authenticate all viewers transparently using Windows pass-through authentication."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly lists 'embed credentials for live connections (or prompt user)' as an option available when publishing a workbook via Server > Publish Workbook. Choosing 'Embed credentials' stores the database credentials within the published workbook on the server, allowing all viewers to access live data without being individually prompted. 'Prompt user' is the opposite behavior — it requires each viewer to supply credentials. Converting to an extract removes the live connection entirely, which changes the data refresh model and is not always acceptable. Tableau Bridge is for network connectivity from Tableau Cloud to on-premises sources, not for credential embedding or Windows pass-through in this context.$patch$, $patch$Publish and Manage Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/publish_workbooks_share.htm","label":"Publish a Workbook to Tableau Server — Tableau Help"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau Site Administrator is publishing a workbook to Tableau Server and must embed database credentials so that all viewers see live data without being prompted to log in to the database. During the publish dialog, which option accomplishes this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A workbook on Tableau Server needs to be moved from the 'Development' project to the 'Production' project. The author navigates to the workbook, selects it, and looks for the option to relocate it. Which action provides this capability in the Tableau Server web interface?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Select the workbook and choose Actions > Move."},{"id":"b","text":"Open the workbook in Tableau Desktop and use File > Save As to point to the new project."},{"id":"c","text":"Download the workbook, delete it, and republish it to the new project."},{"id":"d","text":"Right-click the workbook and select 'Copy to Project'."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In the Tableau Server and Tableau Cloud web interface, you can select one or more workbooks, then use the 'Actions' menu and choose 'Move' to relocate them to a different project without having to download and re-upload. Using Tableau Desktop's 'Save As' would create a new separate publication. Downloading, deleting, and republishing is a manual workaround and risks losing view counts and permissions history. 'Copy to Project' is not an available action in the interface.$patch$, $patch$Publish and Manage Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/qs_content_page.htm#move-content","label":"Tableau Help – Move Content"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A workbook on Tableau Server needs to be moved from the 'Development' project to the 'Production' project. The author navigates to the workbook, selects it, and looks for the option to relocate it. Which action provides this capability in the Tableau Server web interface?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst has published a data source to Tableau Cloud and now wants to certify it so that other users can trust it as an authoritative source. Which role is required to certify a published data source in Tableau Cloud?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Viewer with Write permission on the data source."},{"id":"b","text":"Explorer with Download Full Data capability."},{"id":"c","text":"Site Administrator Explorer or Creator with Overwrite permission on the data source."},{"id":"d","text":"Any Creator who originally published the data source."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Data source certification is an administrative trust feature. To certify a published data source in Tableau Cloud or Tableau Server, the user must have a site role of at least Site Administrator Explorer, or be a Creator who has the Overwrite permission on that data source. Viewers cannot certify content regardless of permissions. A plain Explorer role without the appropriate permissions is insufficient. The original publisher has no special certification privilege unless they also meet the role/permission criteria.$patch$, $patch$Publish and Manage Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/server/en-us/datasource_certified.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Certify Data Sources"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst has published a data source to Tableau Cloud and now wants to certify it so that other users can trust it as an authoritative source. Which role is required to certify a published data source in Tableau Cloud?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau Cloud site administrator wants to prevent any published workbook within a specific project from being downloaded by viewers as a Tableau workbook file (.twbx). Which permission capability should be explicitly denied for the Viewer group at the project level to enforce this restriction?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"View"},{"id":"b","text":"Download Image/PDF"},{"id":"c","text":"Download Workbook/Save a Copy"},{"id":"d","text":"Share Customized"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The 'Download Workbook/Save a Copy' capability controls whether a user can download the workbook as a .twbx or .twb file. Denying this capability at the project level (in a locked project) prevents viewers from downloading the workbook file while still allowing them to view it in the browser. 'View' controls basic content visibility and should not be denied if users need to see the content. 'Download Image/PDF' controls image and PDF exports, not workbook file downloads. 'Share Customized' controls the ability to share custom views.$patch$, $patch$Publish and Manage Content$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/server/en-us/permissions_capabilities.htm#workbooks","label":"Tableau Help – Permissions Capabilities Reference (Workbooks)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau Cloud site administrator wants to prevent any published workbook within a specific project from being downloaded by viewers as a Tableau workbook file (.twbx). Which permission capability should be explicitly denied for the Viewer group at the project level to enforce this restriction?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau analyst sets the 'Cardinality' in a relationship between an Orders table and an Order Details table to 'Many to Many'. What is the implication of this setting on the data model?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Tableau will enforce referential integrity and reject records that don't match."},{"id":"b","text":"Tableau will use the cardinality hint to optimize query generation but will still return accurate results."},{"id":"c","text":"Tableau will automatically deduplicate all rows before joining the tables."},{"id":"d","text":"Tableau will always generate a LEFT JOIN regardless of the relationship clause."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Cardinality settings in Tableau relationships (One to One, One to Many, Many to Many) are performance hints that inform Tableau's query optimizer about the nature of the relationship. Tableau uses these hints to generate more efficient SQL. However, setting cardinality does not enforce referential integrity, deduplicate rows, or change the join type generated. The results remain accurate regardless of the cardinality setting chosen.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/relate_tables.htm","label":"Tableau – Relate Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A Tableau analyst sets the 'Cardinality' in a relationship between an Orders table and an Order Details table to 'Many to Many'. What is the implication of this setting on the data model?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst is connecting Tableau Desktop to a JSON file. After connecting, they notice that some nested array fields are represented as aggregated strings rather than individual rows. What Tableau feature should the analyst use to properly expand nested JSON arrays into individual rows?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use the 'Split' option on the aggregated column in the data source page."},{"id":"b","text":"Apply a wildcard union to merge the nested arrays."},{"id":"c","text":"Use Tableau Prep Builder to parse and unnest the nested array fields."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable the 'Flatten JSON' option in the live connection settings."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Tableau Prep Builder provides robust tools for parsing complex JSON structures, including unnesting (expanding) nested arrays into individual rows. Tableau Desktop's native JSON connector can handle simple JSON structures but has limitations with deeply nested arrays. Splitting a column deals with string delimiter splitting, not structural JSON expansion. Wildcard union merges files, not nested structures. There is no 'Flatten JSON' toggle in standard Tableau Desktop live connection settings.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/prep/en-us/prep_connect.htm","label":"Tableau Prep – Connect to Data and Set Up Your Flow"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst is connecting Tableau Desktop to a JSON file. After connecting, they notice that some nested array fields are represented as aggregated strings rather than individual rows. What Tableau feature should the analyst use to properly expand nested JSON arrays into individual rows?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$While building a data source in Tableau Desktop, an analyst drags two tables from different database connections onto the canvas. What Tableau feature does this leverage?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Data blending"},{"id":"b","text":"Cross-database join"},{"id":"c","text":"Wildcard union"},{"id":"d","text":"Tableau Prep flow"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Cross-database joins allow you to join tables from different connections within a single Tableau data source by dragging tables from multiple connection panes onto the canvas. This is distinct from data blending, which operates at the worksheet level and uses aggregated secondary sources. The source material explicitly lists 'Cross-database joins: join across different connections in a single data source.' Wildcard unions combine files matching a name pattern. Tableau Prep is a separate application.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/joining_tables.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Join Your Data (Cross-Database Joins)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$While building a data source in Tableau Desktop, an analyst drags two tables from different database connections onto the canvas. What Tableau feature does this leverage?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst is working with an Excel file that has merged cells, promotional banners in the top rows, and a footer row with totals. Which Tableau Data Source page feature will automatically clean this structure?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Pivot"},{"id":"b","text":"Split"},{"id":"c","text":"Data Interpreter"},{"id":"d","text":"Wildcard Union"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Data Interpreter is designed to automatically detect and remove common Excel formatting issues including merged cells, extraneous headers, footers, and promotional rows. The source material states: 'Data Interpreter: auto-clean Excel data (remove headers, footers, merged cells).' Pivot converts wide data to long format. Split parses text columns by delimiter. Wildcard Union combines files matching a name pattern.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/data_interpreter.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Use Data Interpreter to Clean Your Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analyst is working with an Excel file that has merged cells, promotional banners in the top rows, and a footer row with totals. Which Tableau Data Source page feature will automatically clean this structure?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A dataset contains monthly sales figures spread across 12 separate columns (Jan_Sales, Feb_Sales, … Dec_Sales). An analyst wants to restructure this into two columns: Month and Sales_Value. Which Data Source page operation achieves this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Split"},{"id":"b","text":"Union"},{"id":"c","text":"Pivot"},{"id":"d","text":"Data Interpreter"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Pivot transforms wide (columnar) data into long (row-based) data by taking multiple columns and converting them into a single column of values plus a column of field names. The source material says: 'Pivot: transform wide data to long (multiple columns → one column).' This exactly matches the requirement of turning 12 month columns into two columns (Month and Sales_Value). Split parses text by delimiter. Union stacks tables. Data Interpreter cleans Excel formatting.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/pivot.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Pivot Data from Columns to Rows"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'TDA-C01-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A dataset contains monthly sales figures spread across 12 separate columns (Jan_Sales, Feb_Sales, … Dec_Sales). An analyst wants to restructure this into two columns: Month and Sales_Value. Which Data Source page operation achieves this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analyst notices a cell in a blended view displays an asterisk (*) instead of a dimension value. What does this indicate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The field is null in the primary data source."},{"id":"b","text":"The secondary data source returned multiple matching values for that dimension."},{"id":"c","text":"The linking field was not configured correctly."},{"id":"d","text":"The field type is Boolean and has been suppressed."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In a data blend, the secondary data source aggregates its data before joining to the primary. When multiple rows in the secondary source match a single row in the primary, Tableau cannot resolve them to a single dimension value and displays an asterisk (*). The source material confirms: '"*" in cell = multiple values blended (Asterisks).' This is not a null indicator, a linking configuration error, or a Boolean display issue.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/multipleconnections_troubleshooting.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Troubleshoot Data Blending"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
