  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau extract (.hyper file) has been published to Tableau Server. The underlying database adds new rows each night. The analyst wants to refresh only the newly added rows rather than re-extracting the entire dataset each time. Which refresh strategy should be configured?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Full extract refresh on a weekly schedule"},{"id":"b","text":"Live connection switch"},{"id":"c","text":"Incremental extract refresh using a date/ID column to identify new rows"},{"id":"d","text":"Wildcard union refresh"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Incremental extract refresh appends only new rows to an existing .hyper extract by comparing a specified column (such as a date or auto-incrementing ID) to identify records added since the last refresh. This avoids the overhead of a full re-extraction. The source material notes: 'Extract (.hyper file, in-memory snapshot, faster, supports incremental refresh).' A full refresh re-processes all rows. Switching to a live connection removes the extract benefit. Wildcard union is for combining files, not for refreshing.$patch$, $patch$Connect to and Transform Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/extracting_refresh.htm","label":"Tableau Help – Refresh Extracts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
