  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A Tableau analyst wants to count the number of distinct customer IDs in a view. Which aggregation function should they use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"COUNT([Customer ID])"},{"id":"b","text":"COUNTD([Customer ID])"},{"id":"c","text":"SUM([Customer ID])"},{"id":"d","text":"ATTR([Customer ID])"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$COUNTD returns the number of distinct (unique) values in a field, making it the correct choice for counting unique customer IDs. COUNT returns the total number of non-null values including duplicates. SUM adds numeric values together and is not applicable for counting. ATTR returns the value of the field if all rows have the same value, otherwise returns an asterisk — it is not a counting function. The source material lists COUNTD explicitly under Aggregation functions.$patch$, $patch$Explore and Analyze Data$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://help.tableau.com/current/pro/desktop/en-us/functions_functions_aggregate.htm","label":"Tableau – Aggregate Functions"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
